06796nam a22009135i 9789048529056DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20202020ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485290567 a10.1515/97890485290562doi  a(DE-B1597)548863  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aART0570002bisacsh0484pa791.436qDE-10100aScreen Space Reconfigured /ced. by Synne Tollerud Bull, Susanne Saether. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (332 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMediaMatters00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Screen Space Reconfigured -- t1. Surface Tension, Screen Space -- t2. Knowing Not What To Believe : Digital Space and Entanglement in Life of Pi, Gravity, and Interstellar -- t3. Digital 3D, Parallax Effects, and the Construction of Film Space in Tangled 3D and Cave of Forgotten Dreams 3D -- t4. Reconfigurations of Screen Borders: The New or Not-So-New Aspect Ratios -- t5. Face, Frame, Fragment: Refiguring Space in Found-Footage Cinema -- t6. Looking Up, Looking Down: A New Vision in Motion -- t7. Surface Explorations: 3D Moving Images as Cartographies of Time -- t8. Touch/Space: The Haptic in 21st-Century Video Art -- t9. Screenic (Re)orientations : Desktop, Tabletop, Tablet, Booklet, Touchscreen, Etc -- t10. 'Nothing Will Have Taken Place - Except Place ': The Unsettling Nature of Camera Movement -- t11. The Phantasmagoric Dispositif : An Assembly of Bodies and Images in Real Time and Space -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aScreen Space Reconfigured is the first edited volume that critically and theoretically examines the many novel renderings of space brought to us by 21st century screens. Exploring key cases such as post-perspectival space, 3D, vertical framing, haptics, and layering, this volume takes stock of emerging forms of screen space and spatialities as they move from the margins to the centre of contemporary media practice.[-]Recent years have seen a marked scholarly interest in spatial dimensions and conceptions of moving image culture, with some theorists claiming that a 'spatial turn' has taken place in media studies and screen practices alike. Yet this is the first book-length study dedicated to on-screen spatiality as such.[-]Spanning mainstream cinema, experimental film, video art, mobile screens, and stadium entertainment, the volume includes contributions from such acclaimed authors as Giuliana Bruno and Tom Gunning as well as a younger generation of scholars.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aFilm Studies. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aMedia Studies. 7aART / Film & Video.2bisacsh  a3D.  aAerial View.  aHaptics.  aPost-perspectival.  aScreen space.1 aBrown, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBruno, Giuliana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBull, Synne T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBull, Synne Tollerud, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCameron, Allan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Rosa, Miriam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElcott, Noam M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGunning, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPranolo, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb